==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=rotten}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|roten|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|non}} {{term|rotinn||decayed, rotten|lang=non}}, past participle of an unrecorded verb related to {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|rotna||to rot|lang=non}} and {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|rotian||to rot|lang=ang}}. More at {{l|en|rot}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|ɒtən}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er|more}}

# Of perishable items, overridden with [[bacteria]] and other infectious agents.
#: ''If you leave a bin unattended for a few weeks, the rubbish inside will turn '''rotten'''.''
# In a state of [[decay]].
#: ''The floors were damaged and the walls were '''rotten'''.''
#: ''His mouth stank and his teeth were '''rotten'''.''
# [[cruel|Cruel]], [[mean]] or [[immoral]].
#: ''That man is a '''rotten''' father.''
#: ''This '''rotten''' policy will create more injustice in this country.''
# [[bad|Bad]] or [[terrible]].
#: ''Why is the weather always '''rotten''' in this city?''
#: ''It was a '''rotten''' idea to take the boat out today.''
#: ''She has the flu and feels '''rotten'''.''

====Usage notes====
* Nouns to which "rotten" is often applied: wood, food, egg, meat, fruit, tomato, apple, banana, milk, vegetable, stuff, tooth, smell, person, kid, bastard, scoundrel, weather.

